    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-01-06T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-01-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="763"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d763">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.9111/47: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-01-06">January 6,
                            1943</date>.<lb/>[Received 10:44 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>20. [Here follows report on editorial in the <hi rend="italic">Ta Kung Pao</hi>
                    of January 5.]</p>
                <p>Sun Fo, President of Legislative Yuan, in New Year’s message, decries suggesting
                    that Manchuria should be governed by Russia after war, criticises, as unjust,
                    American magazine article proposing inclusion of Thailand in new state with
                    Malaya, British and Dutch [East] Indies and strongly opposes inclusion of
                    Formosa in defense area across Pacific suggested in same article. He states
                    recovery of Manchuria and Formosa unchangeable aim of China’s revolution and
                    Thailand as once independent state should not be destroyed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
